some calcification. The normal testicular tissue has been replaced. Tumour marker studies are all within normal range and a chest X-ray is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Needle biopsy","CT abdomen and pelvis","MRI abdomen, pelvis and scrotum","Transcrotal exploration","Inguinal orchidectomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EEven without any further investigations, this young man almost certainly has a testicular cancer. The ultrasound findings fit well for a non-seminomatous tumour. One-third of these patients will have tumour markers (human chorionic gonadotropin, alpha-fetoprotein, lactate dehydrogenase) within the normal range. Once the diagnosis of testicular cancer is suspected, a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eof\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ethe\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdomen\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eand\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Epelvis\u003C/strong\u003E should be the next investigation. When histological proof of the disease is required, this must be obtained by a trans-inguinal orchidectomy. Anything less than that risks spillage of tumour and spread of the disease across tissue planes; thereby compromising treatment. An MRI would add little in this case, but this investigation could be of value if ultrasound findings are inconclusive or the clinical examination is inconsistent.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A CT scan abdomen and pelvis is an essential staging investigation for testicular cancer that must precede other interventions."],"references":["Hanna NH, Einhorn LH. Testicular Cancer - Discoveries and Updates. N Engl J Med 2014; 371:2005-16.","Tsili AC, Argyropoulou MI, Dolciami M, Ercolani G, Catalano C, Manganaro L. When to ask for an MRI of the scrotum. Andrology. 2021; 